## Comparison with Other JOINs

| JOIN Type | Tables | Condition | Purpose |
|-----------|--------|-----------|---------|
| **INNER JOIN** | 2 different | ON/USING | Matching rows only |
| **LEFT JOIN** | 2 different | ON/USING | All from left + matches |
| **SELF JOIN** | Same table | ON condition | Compare rows within same table |
| **CROSS JOIN** | 2 different | NONE | All combinations |

---

## Common SELF JOIN Scenarios

✅ **Manager-Employee Relationships**
```sql
SELECT e.name, m.name FROM employee e 
JOIN employee m ON e.manager_id = m.employee_id;
```

✅ **Organizational Hierarchy**
```sql
SELECT parent.name, child.name FROM org o1 
JOIN org o2 ON o1.id = o2.parent_id;
```

✅ **Find Duplicate/Related Records**
```sql
SELECT e1.name, e2.name FROM employee e1 
JOIN employee e2 ON e1.department = e2.department;
```

✅ **Comparisons**
```sql
SELECT e1.name, e2.name FROM employee e1 
JOIN employee e2 ON e1.salary = e2.salary;
```

---

## Summary

- **SELF JOIN** = Join a table with itself
- **Requires aliases** to distinguish table instances
- **Common uses**: Hierarchies, manager-employee, comparisons
- **Can use**: INNER, LEFT, RIGHT, FULL OUTER joins
- **WHERE clause**: Usually includes `e1.id < e2.id` to avoid duplicates

